{
  "texts": [
    "Returning to our new definition Γ, this seems a little strange: the correlation function has poles at noninsertion points, a feature which requires explanation.",
    "In fact, these poles are a consequence of having extended the worldsheet theory to be described by the bosonization (2.19), which introduces background charges at the preimages of the point at infinity on the boundarysee section 2.3.3.",
    "These represent spurious singularities as we will discuss in section 5.2, and can be explained by the presence of the insertions (2.26).",
    "We will also discuss a spacetime interpretation for these poles in section 5.3.Before proceeding, it is worth noting that e -Σ was found to be the boundary coordinate γ(z) of the Wakimoto representation in (2.21).",
    "This boundary coordinate was found to act as an operator version of the covering map in [4,14]:γ(z) n-2 α=1 W (u α) n i=1 V w i m i 1,m i 2 (x i; z i) = Γ(z) n-2 α=1 W (u α) n i=1 V w i m i 1,m i 2 (x i; z i), (4.14)giving the semi-classical solution γ(z) ≈ Γ(z)."
  ]
}